-- Yashili Surges as Investments Lift Trading Halt: Hong Kong Mover
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2013-11-11T03:07:09Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-11-11/yashili-surges-as-investments-lift-trading-halt-hong-kong-mover.html
Yashili International Holdings Ltd. (1230) 
surged to a record in  Hong Kong  after investors including
Temasek Holdings Pte agreed to buy shares, resuming trading
halted since Aug. 15.  China Mengniu Dairy Co. (2319) , Yashili’s parent, agreed to sell
HK$1.65 billion ($212 million) in shares to meet the minimum
amount of stock in circulation. Yashili surged as much as 23
percent to HK$4.45, headed for the highest close since its
November 2010 initial public offering, before trading at HK$4.09
at 9:51 a.m. local time.  A unit of Singapore’s state-run fund Temasek and investors
including Vitel Group Ltd. will buy the shares from Mengniu,
according to a statement from the parent to the Hong Kong stock
exchange today. Companies based in and outside the country are
seeking to profit from surging demand in a baby formula market
Euromonitor International estimates will rise by more than 70
percent to 133.5 billion  yuan  ($22 billion) by 2015.  The sale was at HK$3.50 per share and brought Mengniu’s
holding to about 77 percent, according to the statement.  Mengniu,  China ’s largest dairy company, agreed to pay
HK$12.5 billion for 100 percent of Yashili in June to build a
bigger presence in an infant milk market.  A Temasek unit will buy 220 million Yashili shares while
Vitel, an affiliate of the Hopu private-equity fund, will buy
177.4 million shares, according to the statement.  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
